<TITLE> Gilchrist smashes century in hometown farewell </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 SYDNEY, Feb 15 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Adam Gilchrist scored a brilliant century in his final hometown appearance before Australia's lower-order batting sudddenly collapsed in Friday's tri-series one-day international against Sri Lanka. Gilchrist capped his last appearance at the WACA in Perth with a superb 118 but got little support from his team mates as Australia crumbled to be all out for 236. Michael Clarke made 43 and Ricky Ponting and Mike Hussey chipped in with 25 each but none of the remaining seven batsmen made it to double figures. Lasith Malinga was the standout bowler for the Sri Lankans, capturing four wickets for 47 runs with his unusual round-arm action, while Nuwan Kulasekera claimed two scalps. Gilchrist announced last month he was retiring from international cricket after the tri-series but was determined to make a big impression in his last match at the WACA. With his family watching from the stands, Gilchrist tore into Sri Lanka's bowlers with a brutal but controlled display, hitting nine boundaries and three sixes. He brought up his 16th one-day international hundred off 117 balls before eventually falling to Malinga while trying to increase the scoring rate. Gilchrist's departure triggered a batting collapse and the Australians lost their last six wickets for just 30 runs to be all out in the last ove
